'''Toni Michele Braxton''' (born October 7, 1967)<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Derrick Bryson|title=Happy 45th Birthday, Toni Braxton!|url=http://www.essence.com/2012/10/07/happy-45th-birthday-toni-braxton/|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[Essence (magazine){{!}}Essence]]|date=October 7, 2012}}</ref> is an American [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] [[singer-songwriter]], [[pianist]], [[musician]], [[record producer]], [[actress]], [[television personality]], and [[philanthropist]]. Braxton has won six [[Grammy Award]]s, seven [[American Music Awards]], and nine [[Billboard Music Awards]]. Throughout the years, she has sold over 66 million records worldwide establishing herself as an R&B icon. Braxton was one of the best-selling female artist of the 1990s, garnering her honorific titles such as the "Queen of R&B".

Braxton topped the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with her 1993 [[Toni Braxton (album)|self-titled debut studio album]] and its hit singles "[[Love Shoulda Brought You Home]]", "[[Another Sad Love Song]]", "[[Breathe Again]]" and "[[You Mean the World to Me]]". She continued that streak with her second studio album, ''[[Secrets (Toni Braxton album)|Secrets]]'', which spawned the number-one hits "[[You're Makin' Me High]]" and "[[Unbreak My Heart]]" in 1996. Although she had successful albums and singles, Braxton filed for bankruptcy in 1998, but then returned with her chart-topping third album, ''[[The Heat (Toni Braxton album)|The Heat]]'' in 2000, which included the international hit single "[[He Wasn't Man Enough]]". In 2009, she returned to the spotlight with "[[Yesterday (Toni Braxton song)|Yesterday]]", a No. 12 R&B hit which served as the first single from her new album ''[[Pulse (Toni Braxton album)|Pulse]]'', released on May 4, 2010, which debuted at No. 1 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' R&B Album Chart.<ref name="radio1.gr">{{cite web|author=Praxis Media |url=http://www.radio1.gr/music/forthcoming_uk_albums.htm |title=Radio1 Rodos Greece ::: UK Forthcoming Albums ::: Charts, DJ Promos, Dance, Lyrics, Free Mp3 Samples Downloads |publisher=Radio1.gr |date= |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref> Braxton was involved in the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 7)|7th season]] of the reality show ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]''. Her professional partner was [[Alec Mazo]]. She was voted off in week five of the competition. It was announced on October 6, 2010 that Braxton had once again filed for bankruptcy and was reporting somewhere between $1<U+2013>$50 million in debts. Braxton was later discharged of her debt. A reality series entitled ''[[Braxton Family Values]]'', starring Toni and her sisters, debuted April 12, 2011 on [[WE tv]]. WE tv ordered a 13-episode second season of the show after the third episode of the first season. On September 18, 2011, Braxton was inducted into the [[Georgia Music Hall of Fame]]. Braxton released the single "Hurt You" from her upcoming duet album with [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] entitled ''[[Love, Marriage & Divorce]]'' and as of December 2013 it marks her seventh ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Adult R&B No. 1 on the chart.

==Early life==
Braxton and her siblings were raised in a strict religious household,<ref name="psu">{{cite web|url=http://www.premiumseatsusa.com/concert/Toni-Braxton/ |title=Toni Braxton Tickets|accessdate=December 18, 2006|format=|work=Premium Seats USA}}</ref> and Braxton's first performing experience was singing in her church choir.<ref name="psu"/>

She was born in [[Severn, Maryland]].{{citation needed|date=February 2013}} Her father, Michael Conrad Braxton, Sr., was a [[Methodist]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adherents.com/largecom/fam_meth.html |title=Famous Methodists |publisher=Adherents.com |date= |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jet|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=I7sDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA21|accessdate=December 2, 2013|date=June 20, 1994|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|page=21|id={{ISSN|00215996}}}}</ref> clergyman and power company worker, and her mother, Evelyn Jackson, a native of [[South Carolina]], was a former opera singer and cosmetologist, as well as a pastor.<ref>{{cite news| last=Dougherty|first=Steve|title=Greener Pastures| url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20132603,00.html| accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[People (magazine){{!}}People]]|date=October 9, 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Braxton Family Values <U+2013> Evelyn Braxton|url=http://www.wetv.com/shows/braxton-family-values/cast/evelyn-braxton|work=[[WE tv]]|publisher=AMC Networks|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref> Braxton's maternal grandfather was also a pastor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ney|first=Angela Winter|title=Award-winning pastor reaches out to teen-agers|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-02-06/news/1994037080_1_toni-braxton-inside-the-church-award|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]]|date=February 6, 1994}}</ref>

Braxton is the eldest of six siblings.  She has a younger brother Michael, Jr. (born in 1968) and four younger sisters [[Traci Braxton|Traci]] (born in 1971), [[Towanda Braxton|Towanda]] (born in 1973), [[Trina Braxton|Trina]] (born in 1974), and [[Tamar Braxton|Tamar]] (born in 1977).  Braxton attended [[Bowie State University]] to obtain a teaching degree,<ref>{{Cite news|first=Joy Bennett|last=Kinnon|title=The Rise and Fall and Rise of Toni Braxton|work=Ebony |date= December 2000|accessdate=June 6, 2009}}</ref> but decided to sing professionally after she was discovered by William E. Pettaway, Jr., who reportedly heard her singing to herself while pumping gas.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Morgan|last=Joan|title=Fully Exposed|work=Vibe|date= December 2002|accessdate=June 6, 2009|quote=One day in 1990, songwriter Bill Pettaway heard Toni singing to herself at an Annapolis gas station, liked what he heard, and got her an audition with L.A.}}</ref>

But according to Braxton during her appearance on the 24 May 2014 broadcast of [[NPR]]'s [[Wait, Wait, Don't Tell Me]], she was not singing to herself at the gas station. Pettaway, working as an attendant at the [[Annapolis]] service station where she was refueling, recognized her from local performances and introduced himself, saying he wanted to produce her. Though skeptical, Braxton decided to, in her words, "take a chance" and accepted.

==Career==

===1989<U+2013>95: ''The Braxtons'' and album debut ''Toni Braxton''===
{{Main|The Braxtons}}
Braxton and her four sisters (Traci, Towanda, Trina, and Tamar) began performing as ''[[The Braxtons]]'' in the late 1980s and were signed to [[Arista Records]] in 1989. Their first single, "[[Good Life (The Braxtons song)|Good Life]]", was released in 1990.<ref name="vibe">{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/music/search/artist.html?id=UCAgICAzNzU3Ng |title=Toni Braxton |accessdate=December 18, 2006 |work=VIBE.com }}{{dead link|date=November 2012}}</ref> Though the song was not successful, it attracted the attention of [[Antonio "L.A." Reid]] and [[Kenneth "Babyface" Edmonds]].<ref name="vibe"/> Reid and Babyface recruited her to record a demo of "Love Shoulda Brought You Home", a song that they had written for Anita Baker for the soundtrack of [[Eddie Murphy]]'s film, ''[[Boomerang (1992 film)|Boomerang]]''. Baker, who was pregnant at the time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.askmen.com/women/singer/8c_toni_braxton.html |title=Toni Braxton |accessdate=December 18, 2006 |work=AskMen }}</ref> did not record the song but suggested, that Braxton record it. Her recording was later included on the soundtrack along with "[[Give U My Heart]]", a duet by Braxton and Babyface. Braxton, meanwhile, was signed to Reid and Edmonds' Arista-distributed imprint, [[LaFace Records]], and immediately began recording her solo debut album.

On July 13, 1993, LaFace Records released Braxton's self-titled debut album, ''[[Toni Braxton (album)|Toni Braxton]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Toni-Braxton/dp/B0000013G5|title=''Toni Braxton'': Music: Toni Braxton |accessdate=December 18, 2006|format=|work=Amazon.com}}</ref> The album, which was primarily produced by Reid, [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]], and [[Daryl Simmons]], peaked at number one on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?pid=30331&aid=146011|title=Discography&nbsp;<U+2014> Toni Braxton - ''Toni Braxton''|accessdate=December 18, 2006|format=|work=Billboard.com |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070929141413/http://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?pid=30331&aid=146011 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 29, 2007}}</ref> The first single, "[[Another Sad Love Song]]", peaked at number seven and number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks|R&B Singles]] charts respectively.<ref name="billboard singles">{{cite web|url=http://billboard.com/bbcom/retrieve_chart_history.do?model.vnuArtistId=30331&model.vnuAlbumId=146011 |title=Artist Chart History&nbsp;<U+2014> Toni Braxton |accessdate=December 18, 2006 |work=Billboard.com}}{{dead link|date=November 2012}}</ref> The album's second single, "[[Breathe Again]]" peaked in the top five of both the Hot 100 and R&B singles charts<ref name="billboard singles"/> and no 2 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com |title=UK Top 40 Chart Archive, British Singles & Album Charts |publisher=Everyhit.com |date=March 16, 2000 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> More singles from ''Toni Braxton'' were released in 1994, including "[[You Mean the World to Me]]", "[[Seven Whole Days]]", "[[I Belong to You (Toni Braxton song)|I Belong to You]]", and "[[How Many Ways]]".<ref name="billboard singles"/>

Braxton's debut album won her several awards, including three [[Grammy Award]]s (for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] and two consecutive awards for [[Grammy Award for Best Female R&B Vocal Performance|Best Female R&B Vocal Performance]] in 1994 and 1995).<ref name="YTV">{{cite web|url=http://tv.yahoo.com/toni-braxton/contributor/38261/awards|title=Toni Braxton|accessdate=December 26, 2006|work=Yahoo! TV|date=March 14, 2003}}</ref> She also won two [[American Music Award]]s (for Favorite Soul/R&B New Artist and Favorite New Adult Contemporary Artist)<ref name="YTV"/> in 1994 and another one in 1995 (for Favorite Soul/R&B Album).<ref name="YTV"/> ''Toni Braxton'' was certified 8x platinum in USA and has sales of over 10 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.com/gp/bestsellers/topalbums.asp|title=Gold&Platinum: Top 100 albums|accessdate=December 18, 2006|format=|work=RIAA |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061214122646/http://www.riaa.com/gp/bestsellers/topalbums.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = December 14, 2006}}</ref><ref name="books.google.com">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ArUDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA56&dq=toni+braxton+sold&hl=pt-BR&ei=kBKETJGqLoP98Ab5vb2aAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=toni%20braxton%20sold&f=false |title=Jet&nbsp;<U+2014> Google Livros |publisher=Books.google.com |date=July 17, 2000 |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref>

===1996<U+2013>99: ''Secrets'', Broadway, and Bankruptcy===

In June 1996, Braxton released her second and most successful album, ''[[Secrets (Toni Braxton album)|Secrets]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/dp/B0000013GH/ |title=''Secrets'': Music: Toni Braxton |accessdate=December 18, 2006 |work=Amazon.com }}</ref> Braxton has said about the album: "The motivation for this album was to include a little bit of everything. Our aim was to come up with material, that would have a familiar 'feel' to the people, who bought the first album without being musically redundant."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-b/tonibraxton_main.htm |title=Toni Braxton |accessdate=December 18, 2006|work=Rock on the Net }}</ref> Along with Babyface, Braxton also worked with [[R. Kelly]], [[Tony Rich]], and [[David Foster]] on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,230175,00.html?src=search#credits |title=Toni Braxton: ''Secrets''|accessdate=December 18, 2006|format=|work=ArtistDirect }}</ref> Braxton was the co-executive producer of the album and co-wrote two of its songs, including the 1997 single "How Could an Angel Break My Heart", which was also later included on ''Diana Princess of Wales Tribute'', a [[Princess Diana]] memorial album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/dp/B000002C4U|title=''Diana Princess of Wales Tribute''|accessdate=December 18, 2006|format=|work=Amazon.com}}</ref>
With help from the album's first single, "[[You're Makin' Me High]]" (which became Braxton's first number-one hit on the Hot 100 singles chart),<ref name="billboard singles"/> the album peaked at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?JSESSIONID=FHJ2kFF9nFq0gg5KtPxXY8nGJ2sqxnQLL1brcY1T26XLrc1Q1lcF!-1562377538&pid=30331&aid=185866|title=Discography&nbsp;<U+2014> Toni Braxton - ''Secrets''|accessdate=December 18, 2006|format=|work=Billboard.com |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070929141203/http://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?JSESSIONID=FHJ2kFF9nFq0gg5KtPxXY8nGJ2sqxnQLL1brcY1T26XLrc1Q1lcF!-1562377538&pid=30331&aid=185866 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 29, 2007}}</ref> "You're Makin' Me High" also topped the R&B singles chart for two weeks<ref name="billboard singles"/> and saw similar success in Europe and Asia. The album's second single, "[[Un-Break My Heart]]" (written by [[Diane Warren]]) became the biggest hit of her career spending eleven weeks at number one on the Hot 100<ref name="vibe"/> and also topping the [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]] chart for eleven weeks and the [[Hot Dance Music/Club Play]] chart for four weeks<ref name="mfc">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicfanclubs.org/tonibraxton/timeline.htm|title=Toni Braxton|accessdate=December 26, 2006 |work=Music Fan Clubs}}</ref> as well as reaching no 2 in the UK<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com |title=UK Top 40 Chart Archive, British Singles & Album Charts |publisher=everyHit.com |date=2000-03-16 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref> Other singles from the album included the double A-side "[[I Don't Want To]]"/"I Love Me Some Him" (which peaked at number one on the Hot Dance Music/Club Play chart)<ref name="billboard singles"/> and "How Could an Angel Break My Heart", which featured [[Kenny G]], with whom Braxton later toured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://livedesignonline.com/mag/lighting_kenny_toni_lds|title=Kenny G and Toni B: Lds Valerie Groth and Justin Collie manipulate one lighting system to create two shows|accessdate=December 26, 2006|format=|work=Live Design|date=May 1, 1997}}</ref> After 92 weeks in the charts, ''Secrets'' is certified 8x platinum, becoming Braxton's second straight 8 million seller. Internationally, ''Secrets'' sold more than 15 million copies, thus cementing Braxton's superstar status.<ref name="books.google.com"/> Braxton topped the ''Billboard'' Year-End Charts as the Top Hot 100 Singles Artist&nbsp;<U+2014> Female,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=The+Billboard+Hot+100&g=Year-end+Singles&year=1997|title=Year End Charts&nbsp;<U+2014> Year-end Singles&nbsp;<U+2014> The Billboard Hot 100|accessdate=December 26, 2006|format=|work=Billboard.com}}</ref> Top R&B Artist&nbsp;<U+2014> Female (singles and albums),<ref name="mfc"/> Top Hot R&B Singles Artist&nbsp;<U+2014> Female,<ref name="mfc"/> Top Hot Dance Club Play Artist, and Top Hot Adult Contemporary Artist, while "Un-Break My Heart" became the Top Hot Dance Club Play Single and the Top Hot Adult Contemporary Track of the year. She won two Grammy Awards; one for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]]<ref name="YTV"/> and Best Female R&B Vocal Performance and two [[American Music Award]]s for Favorite Female Soul/R&B Artist and Favorite Soul/R&B Album.<ref name="YTV"/>

By 1996, Braxton had sold more than 20 million records. She was still waiting on her financial rewards, eventually launching an unsuccessful lawsuit against Arista and LaFace Records. Soon after, she filed for chapter 7 bankruptcy. Public reaction to these events was very harsh, having been expressed most clearly in an interview on ''Oprah Winfrey Show''.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ftLjr4CQcrQ</ref> Upon successfully filing for bankruptcy, Braxton relinquished the rights to many of her valued possessions, including the Grammys and American Music Awards she had previously been granted.

Braxton has appeared on two [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] shows:  She made her Broadway debut as Belle in ''[[Beauty and the Beast (theatrical production)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' beginning September 9, 1998 when she replaced Kim Huber.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/40798-Braxton-Taylor-Barbour-Beast-to-Be-Unveiled-Sept-9-New-Menken-Song-to-Follow|title=Braxton-Taylor-Barbour Beast to Be Unveiled Sept. 9; New Menken Song to Follow|accessdate=June 27, 2010 |work=playbill}}</ref> During her run in the show [[Alan Menken]] wrote a new song for the musical called "A Change in Me", which was specially written for Braxton and was used in the musical ever since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/41311-Toni-Braxton-Premieres-Beauty-s-New-Song-Oct-7-On-Rosie |title=Toni Braxton Premieres Beauty 's New Song, Oct. 7 On 'Rosie' |publisher=Playbill.com |date= |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> She left the production on February 28, 1999 and was succeeded by [[Andrea McArdle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/43273-Bways-Beauty-Turns-2000-Sat-Matinee-Jan-30-McArdle-Arrives-March-3 |title=Bway's Beauty Turns 2,000 Sat. Matinee Jan. 30; McArdle Arrives March 3 |publisher=Playbill.com |date= |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> Her role in ''Beauty and the Beast'' marked the first (and only) time a black woman commanded the leading role of Belle on Broadway (in the UK, [[Michelle Gayle]] played the role in the West End). It also marked the first time a black woman would star in a Disney musical on Broadway. In 1999, the lawsuit against LaFace Records was settled and Toni was given back all her possessions, giving her time to record her first album in 4 years: The Heat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lifetimetv.com/shows/ip/portraits/0223/0223_bio.html|title=Toni Braxton|accessdate=December 18, 2006|work=Lifetime's intimate portrait}}{{dead link|date=November 2012}}</ref>

===2000<U+2013>01: ''The Heat''===
Finally after a 3 year dispute with LaFace and Arista, it was all settled and Toni signed a new $20 million contract. In March 2000, LaFace Records released "[[He Wasn't Man Enough]]", the first single from Braxton's third studio album, ''[[The Heat (Toni Braxton album)|The Heat]]''. By June 2000, the song peaked at number two on the Hot 100 chart. ''The Heat'' was released on April 25, 2000. Debuting at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 albums chart with first week sales of 194,448 copies sold,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/sales/archcht.cgi?cht692 |title=Previous Album Sales Chart |publisher=HITS Daily Double |date= |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref> it remained in the top 20 for fifteen consecutive weeks. Braxton again worked with producers Babyface and Foster; also included in the staple were [[Rodney Jerkins]], and new beau musician [[Keri Lewis]]. Braxton herself also took a more hands-on approach, co-writing and co-producing a handful of the tracks. "Gimme Some", a track on "The Heat", featured a rap verse from [[TLC (band)|TLC]] star [[Lisa Lopes|Lisa "Left Eye" Lopes]]. The album's second single, "[[Just Be a Man About It]]", peaked at number 32 on the Hot 100 and number six on the R&B Charts. The third single, "[[Spanish Guitar (song)|Spanish Guitar]]", peaked at number 98 on the Hot 100 and number one on the Hot Dance & Club charts. The fourth single, "Maybe", peaked at 74 on the R&B charts. ''The Heat'' was certified double platinum in the US with over three million copies sold worldwide.<ref name="books.google.com"/>

In 2002, while gearing up for the release of her fourth studio album, Braxton discovered she was pregnant with her second child. Knowing that she wouldn't be able to promote the album properly, she unsuccessfully lobbied [[Arista Records]] to get the label to postpone its release until after she was to give birth. [[Arista Records]] refused and the album was released as planned in November 2002. It received very little promotion from Arista and Braxton herself, due to a complicated pregnancy, that's  confined her to [[bed rest]]. Braxton accused the company of being unwilling to compromise and punishing her from not putting her career over family.

===2002<U+2013>06: ''More Than a Woman'', new label, and ''Libra''===
In November 2002, Braxton's fourth studio album ''[[More Than a Woman (album)|More Than a Woman]]'' was released.  Opening to an instant commercial disappointment, the album peaked at number 13.  The first single, [[The Neptunes]] -produced "[[Hit the Freeway]]", failed at radio and peaked at number 86 on the Hot 100. The two singles, that followed ("A Better Man", "Lies, Lies, Lies") were scrapped, failed to make a dent and missed the Hot 100 completely. ''More Than a Woman'' was certified gold by [[RIAA]] and sold more than 800,000 copies worldwide.<ref name="musicmp3.ru">{{cite web|url=http://musicmp3.ru/artist_toni-braxton.html |title=Toni Braxton mp3 music download |publisher=MusicMp3.Ru |date= |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref> Prior to the release of the album, a dispute erupted between Braxton and [[Irv Gotti]], when he played a rough cut of "No More Love", a song that he produced for the album, that was to be the first single. Disapproving of Gotti broadcasting the unfinished track, Braxton withheld it from being released. The same year, Braxton was further annoyed, when [[Jay-Z]] used the same sample of [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]]'s "Me and My Girlfriend", that she had already used on her track "Me & My Boyfriend" for his and Beyonc<U+00E9>'s "[['03 Bonnie & Clyde]]".

She then starred in ''[[Aida (musical)|Aida]]'' as Aida beginning June 30, 2003 when she replaced [[Simone (actress)|Simone]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12037443|title=Toni Braxton Set To Return To Broadway|accessdate=December 19, 2006|format=|work=Yahoo! Music}}{{dead link|date=November 2012}}</ref> and left the cast on November 16, 2003 where she was replaced by [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/82297-Its-Destiny-RB-Singer-Michelle-Williams-to-Replace-Toni-Braxton-in-Aida |title=It's Destiny: R&B Singer Michelle Williams to Replace Toni Braxton in Aida |publisher=Playbill.com |date= |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> In 2001, she made her movie acting debut in the feature film ''[[Kingdom Come (2001 film)|Kingdom Come]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imdb.com/title/tt0246002|title=Kingdom Come|accessdate=December 19, 2006|format=|work=IMDb}}</ref>

In April 2003, Braxton abruptly left Arista Records, having been there for 14 years, and immediately signed with [[Blackground Records]], headed by [[Barry Hankerson]], her manager at the time. The change of scenery, however, did not ultimately help her recording career. As had been the case during her final years at Arista, Braxton's fifth album, and first release on Blackground, ''[[Libra (Toni Braxton album)|Libra]]'' (2005) was released.

In 2004, Braxton appeared as herself, voicing a singing character named Toni, in a special episode and DVD release<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=6760640|title=Blues Clues: Bluestock DVD Movie|accessdate=August 19, 2010|format=|work=CDUniverse.com}}</ref> of the children's television show ''[[Blue's Clues]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0527963/|title="Blue's Clues" Bluestock (2004)|accessdate=August 19, 2010|format=|work=IMDb}}</ref>

In September 2004, it was announced that Braxton would star in a half-hour [[sitcom]] pilot where she would play a version of herself for [[The WB Television Network]]'s fall 2006-07 line-up, though plans to put the show into full-production fell through once The WB announced it would cease to exist in fall 2006 (as part of a merger with [[UPN]] to form [[The CW]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Development Update: September 29-30|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2004/09/30/development-update-september-29-30-17006/6747/|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=November 6, 2013|date=September 30, 2004}}</ref> She has also starred in the TV sitcom, ''Kevin Hill''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/toni.s%20tv%20deal|title=Toni's TV Deal|accessdate=January 24, 2007|format=|work=Contact Music|date=September 20, 2004}}</ref>

In April 2005, Braxton's new label, Blackground/Universal, released "[[Please (Toni Braxton song)|Please]]", the first single from her fifth album, ''[[Libra (Toni Braxton album)|Libra]]''. The album was originally planned for a June release, but it was pushed back several times and was finally issued on September 27. Unfortunately for Braxton, her troubles with weak album promotion and lack of label commitment weren't over. "Please" peaked at number 36 on ''Billboard'' Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs, while altogether missing the Hot 100.

''Libra'' still managed to debut at number four on the ''Billboard'' 200 selling 114,593 copies in the first week. ''Libra'' also peaked at number two on the Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums. Although that is strong for an album with little to no promotion, it became yet another commercial disappointment for Braxton. The album's second single, "[[Trippin' (That's the Way Love Works)]]", received less airplay and peaked at number 67 on the R&B chart. The failure was ascribed to the non-video presence of the single and lack of label support. The album was certified gold in late 2005 and has since sold 679,000 copies worldwide.<ref name="musicmp3.ru"/>

Braxton, meanwhile, recorded a song with [[Il Divo]] titled "[[The Time of Our Lives]]". The song was used as the official [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] anthem and was performed at the championship's opening day in [[Berlin, Germany]] on June 9. The song was also performed at the closing ceremonies making Braxton and Il Divo the first artists to be asked to perform for the opening and closing ceremonies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16862049&method=full&siteid=94762&headline=fiona--divo--name_page.html|title=FIONA: DIVO|accessdate=December 18, 2006 |work=Mirror.co.uk}}</ref>

Braxton made an appearance on the season finale of ''[[American Idol (season 5)|American Idol 5]]'', where she performed [[Elvis Presley]]'s "[[In the Ghetto]]" with soon-to-be winner [[Taylor Hicks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1532468/20060524/hicks__taylor.jhtml|title=Soul Patrol Rides On: Taylor Hicks Wins 'American Idol'|accessdate=December 27, 2006|work=MTV News|date=May 25, 2006}}</ref>

===2006<U+2013>07: ''Toni Braxton: Revealed'' and second bankruptcy===
[[Image:Flamingo Hotel Las Vegas.jpg|right|thumb|[[Flamingo Las Vegas]] at night featuring Braxton, January 2007.]]
On May 19, 2006, the [[Flamingo Las Vegas|Flamingo Hotel and Casino]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] announced that Braxton would replace [[Wayne Newton]] as the casino's new headlining act on August 3, 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toni Braxton to be headliner at Flamingo Las Vegas to 2007|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/travel/hotels/2006-05-19-braxtons-back_x.htm|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=May 19, 2006|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The show, entitled ''Toni Braxton: Revealed'', was to be performed six nights a week and was scheduled to run through March 2007. Braxton Later confirmed that she was extending her show through August 2007. The show became the first headlining show from an African American performer in Las Vegas to enter the top ten Vegas shows charting. Due to the success of the show, it was reported, that Braxton would extend her show through August 2008. The show was later cancelled, and it was announced, that the show was officially shut down in order for the singer to focus on her health.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mascia|first=Kristen|title=Toni Braxton Cancels Vegas Show|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20203349,00.html|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=People|date=May 30, 2008}}</ref>

According to Braxton, via a lawsuit, [[TMZ]], and [[VH1]]'s [[Behind the Music]], after her show was abruptly cancelled, the insurance agency, [[Lloyd's of London]] refused to honor her policy that she purchased for upwards of $70,000 that included financial compensations for financial losses that occurred as results of concert cancellations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toni Braxton: My Insurance Co. Has No Heart|url=http://www.tmz.com/2009/04/29/toni-braxton-lawsuit/|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[TMZ]]|date=April 29, 2009}}</ref> The policy was reported to insure Braxton up to $2.8 million.<ref name="hinterlandgazette.com">{{cite news|last=Shan|first=Janet|title=Legal Briefs: Singer Toni Braxton Sues Lloyd's of London Over Cancelled Shoes|url=http://hinterlandgazette.com/2009/05/legal-briefs-singer-toni-braxton-sues.html|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=The Hinterland Gazette|date=May 3, 2009}}</ref><ref name="vh1.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/behind_the_music/episode.jhtml?episodeID=200331 |title=Ep. 238 &#124; Toni Braxton &#124; Behind The Music &#124; Episode Summary, Highlights, and Recaps |publisher=VH1.com |date= |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> Lloyd's of London responded with a counter-suit seeking damages against Braxton and remarked that Braxton's policy was null and void because of an unrelated heart condition that the company was not made aware of at the time the application was filed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Insurance Co. Claims Braxton's a Hearty Liar|url=http://www.tmz.com/2009/10/01/lloyds-of-london-toni-braxton-lawsuit-heart-condition/|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=TMZ|date=October 1, 2009}}</ref> Braxton responded to the counter-suit by saying that she did disclose her full medical history at the time.<ref name="hinterlandgazette.com"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hellobeautiful.com/509107/lloyds-of-london-sues-toni-braxton/ |title=Lloyds of London Sues Toni Braxton &#124; Celebrity News & Style for Black Women |publisher=Hellobeautiful.com |date=October 1, 2009 |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/toni-braxton-sues-her-insurance-company/article/3816464 |title=Toni Braxton sues her insurance company |publisher=News OK |date=April 29, 2009 |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> As a result of the insurance company nullifying Braxton's contract, Braxton has said that she was on the hook for all damages because of the cancelled shows, being sued by multiple companies, and had to once again file for bankruptcy. As of 2013 Braxton has completed required financial management courses and most of her debt has been discharged.<ref name="vh1.com"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Toni Braxton: My Vegas Show Broke Me|url=http://www.tmz.com/2010/10/07/toni-braxton-files-chapter-7-bankruptcy-las-vegas-show-broke-debt/|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=TMZ|date=October 7, 2010}}</ref>

Braxton was released from her contract with Blackground after a number of disputes with former manager Barry Hankerson in apparent regards to her husband's role in her career.<ref>{{cite news|last=Finn|first=Natalie|title=Braxton Settles Up with Ex-Manager|url=http://au.eonline.com/news/54395/braxton-settles-up-with-ex-manager|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[E! Online]]|date=February 13, 2007}}</ref>

In an October 2006 concert at the [[Flamingo Las Vegas]], Braxton broke down in tears while announcing to the audience that just before the concert began she had been told that her son, Diezel, had been diagnosed with [[autism]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Walls|first=Jeannette|title=O.J. Simpson to confess <U+2014> hypothetically, Plus: Toni Braxton sobs while discussing autistic son|url=http://www.today.com/id/15066202|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[Today.com]]|date=October 30, 2006}}</ref> Braxton has been outspoken regarding her doctor's failure to diagnose Diezel's condition earlier, contending that if he had been diagnosed earlier, he could have been helped better.<ref>{{cite news|title=Braxton Upset With Doctor's Over Son's Autism|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/braxton-upset-with-doctors-over-sons-autism_1009575|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[Contactmusic.com]]|date=September 29, 2006}}</ref> As well as becoming a spokeswoman for [[Autism Speaks]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Toni Braxton Named National Celebrity Spokesperson for Autism Speaks|url=http://www.autismspeaks.org/about-us/press-releases/toni-braxton-named-national-celebrity-spokesperson-autism-speaks|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[Autism Speaks]]|date=March 7, 2007}}</ref> she is also a spokeswoman for the [[American Heart Association]].

In November 2009, Braxton announced through her attorney, Antavius Weems, that she and Lewis had separated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toni Braxton Confirms 'Single' and 'Separated' Post Divorce Rumor|url=http://www.singersroom.com/content/2009-11-20/Toni-Braxton-Confirms-Single-and-Separated-Post-Divorce-Rumor/|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=Singersroom|date=November 20, 2009}}</ref>

On January 12, 2007, Braxton filed a lawsuit in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]] against her former manager Barry Hankerson for $10 million, alleging "fraud, deception and double dealing", in addition to mismanaging her relationship with Arista Records.<ref name=tbmgr>{{cite news|last=Neumeister|first=Larry|title=Toni Braxton Sues Her Former Manager|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/12/AR2007011201814.html|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=January 12, 2007|agency=AP}}</ref> According to Braxton, Hankerson placed his own personal financial interests ahead of hers by using "double-talk" to compromise the relationship between Braxton and her former recording label, [[Arista Records]], with Hankerson allegedly telling Arista that, ''"Braxton no longer wanted to record for Arista"'' and telling Braxton, that ''"Arista was not interested in working with her anymore"''.<ref name=tbmgr/>

The suit was settled with Braxton being forced to return a $375,000 advance to Hankerson, who would also receive a percentage of the sales of her next album, and Hankerson releasing Braxton from her contract with him. The settlement also temporarily limited the companies in which Braxton can sign with.<ref>{{cite news|title=Braxton Settles Lawsuit Against Ex-Manager|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1054986/braxton-settles-lawsuit-against-ex-manager|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=Billboard|date=February 14, 2007|agency=AP}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070113/ap_on_en_mu/braxton_lawsuit_2|title=Toni Braxton sues her former manager|accessdate=January 12, 2007|format=|work=Yahoo|date=January 12, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

===2008<U+2013>10: Dancing with the Stars, Atlantic Records and ''Pulse''===
[[Image:Toni Braxton Soul Beach.JPG|thumb|Soul Beach Music Festival press conference, Toni Braxton with [[Gee Money]], May 2010]]

In August 2008, various internet websites including [[TMZ.com]] and ''[[In Touch Weekly]]'' magazine began announcing, that Braxton would be appearing on the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 7)|seventh season]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. The full cast of the next season of the show was confirmed on August 25, 2008 on ''Good Morning America'', which confirmed Braxton as a contestant in the season with her partner being [[Alec Mazo]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Announcing the Stars|url=http://abc.go.com/primetime/dancingwiththestars/index?pn=announcement|work=abc.go.com|year=2008|accessdate=September 16, 2008}}</ref> They were voted off in the fifth week of the competition.

