In October 2008, it was announced, that Braxton signed to [[Atlantic Records]]. In the November 2008 issue of ''[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]'', Braxton discussed her time spent on ''Dancing with the Stars'' as well as dealing with her son's autism. Braxton also talked about being signed to Atlantic Records and the debut of her upcoming single.

The DJ Frank E produced song "[[Yesterday (Toni Braxton song)|Yesterday]]" premiered on September 11, 2009 and features [[Trey Songz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essence.com/news_entertainment/entertainment/articles/listen_to_toni_braxtons_new_single_yesterday |title=Exclusive: Be the First to Listen to Toni Braxton's New Single 'Yesterday' |accessdate=September 12, 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2012}}</ref> It was released as the lead single from her sixth studio album ''[[Pulse (Toni Braxton album)|Pulse]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/960751/toni-braxton-pulse-album-preview |title=Toni Braxton "Pulse" Album Preview |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> "Yesterday" peaked at No. 12 on the U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart making it her highest chart performance since her 2000 single "[[Just Be a Man About It]]", which peaked at No. 6. The single has been released worldwide on May 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Praxis Media |url=http://www.radio1.gr/music/forthcoming_uk_singles.htm |title=Radio1 Rodos Greece ::: UK Forthcoming Singles ::: Charts, DJ Promos, Dance, Lyrics, Free Mp3 Samples Downloads |publisher=Radio1.gr |date= |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref> In the UK, "Yesterday" became Braxton's first hit single since the release of "[[Hit the Freeway]]", peaking at No. 50 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and at No. 17 on the [[UK R&B Chart|UK R&B Singles Chart]]. The song also became a moderate hit in Europe, peaking at No. 20 on the [[German Singles Chart]], at No. 17 on the [[Swiss Singles Chart]] and charting at No. 50 on the [[European Hot 100]].

On January 29, 2010, Braxton's official website posted two of the songs from the upcoming album, "[[Hands Tied]]" and "Make My Heart". The former peaked at No. 29 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]], the latter was sent to dance/club radio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tonibraxton.com/news/hands-tied-make-my-heart-are-now-available-to-buy-exclusively-on-tonibraxtoncom/ |title="Hands Tied" & "Make My Heart" Are Now Available To Buy Exclusively on ToniBraxton.com! - Blog Detail |publisher=ToniBraxton.com |date=January 29, 2010 |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}{{dead link|date=November 2012}}</ref>
She performed "Make My Heart" on ''[[The Wendy Williams Show]]''.

Braxton released her sixth studio album ''[[Pulse (Toni Braxton album)|Pulse]]'' on May 4, 2010 in the US<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thatgrapejuice.net/2010/01/toni-braxtons-pulse-pushed/ |title=Toni Braxton's 'Pulse' Pushed Back&nbsp;<U+2013> Again &#124; ..::That Grape Juice // ThatGrapeJuice.net::.. &#124;&#124; Thirsty? |publisher=Thatgrapejuice.net |date=January 21, 2010 |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref> and on May 10, 2010 in the UK.<ref name="radio1.gr"/>
Despite the fact that 27 songs were leaked, the album consisting of only 11 tracks, debuted at No. 9 on the US Billboard 200 chart and hit No. 1 on Billboard's [[R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart, becoming Braxton's fifth US top-ten album. It also achieved moderate chart success around the world. In Canada it debuted at No. 72 on the Top 100 Albums chart and in the United Kingdom it debuted at No. 28 on the Top 40 Albums and at No. 7 on the R&B Albums chart. It entered at No. 18 on the German Album Chart. In Switzerland, the album hit No. 9. ''Pulse'', although a commercial flop, became Toni's first album to chart inside the [[European Top 100 Albums]] since her 2000 album ''[[The Heat (Toni Braxton album)|The Heat]]''.

On June 28, 2010, Braxton posted a video for ''Woman''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tonibraxton.com/ |title=Toni Braxton &#124; Official Website: Photos, Blog, Videos, Interactive and more. |publisher=ToniBraxton.com |date= |accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref>

Braxton was included as part of the "[[We Are the World 25 for Haiti]]" remake of the 1985 hit "[[We Are the World]]" to help benefit the people of Haiti following the January 12, 2010 magnitude 7.0 MW earthquake in Haiti. The new version of the song was recorded on February 1, 2010. Music legends [[Quincy Jones]] and [[Lionel Richie]] act as Executive Producers as well as [[Wyclef Jean]]. Artists involved included [[Celine Dion]], [[Barbra Streisand]], [[Janet Jackson]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[Wyclef Jean]], [[Josh Groban]], [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Jennifer Hudson]], [[Adam Levine]], [[Justin Bieber]], [[LL Cool J]], among others.

[[Image:Toni Braxton Romania.jpg|thumb|upright|Braxton performing in [[Romania]] during [[New Year's Eve]] 2011.]]
Later that year rumors began circulating that Braxton was in talks to star in her own reality show with [[Bravo (U.S. TV channel)|Bravo]]. Braxton would later confirm the rumors during an appearance on Ellen after a performance of her single "Make My Heart".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/02/bravo-snags-singer-toni-braxton-for-new-reality-series.html |title=Bravo snags singer Toni Braxton for new reality series [Updated&#93; - Zap2it |publisher=Blog.zap2it.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref>

===2011<U+2013>2012: Reality television success, Initial retirement from music, and Return to acting===
In January 2011, [[WE tv]] confirmed that it had signed Braxton for a [[reality series]], ''[[Braxton Family Values]]'', which is marketed as one of the network's flagship shows. The series debuted April 12, 2011, and looks at the relationship between the singer/songwriter Braxton, her mother, and her four sisters; Trina, [[Tamar Braxton|Tamar]], Traci and Towanda&nbsp;<U+2014> all aspiring singers themselves&nbsp;<U+2014> along with the interpersonal relationships of each family member. The show also looks at Braxton's heavily publicized separation from estranged husband, singer [[Keri Lewis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/01/04/wetv-toni-braxton-staten-island-cakes-tagline/ |title=WEtv unveils new details on Toni Braxton series, new cake series, and announces new tagline|author=James Hibberd|date=January 4, 2011|accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref> Toni parted ways with her long-time manager Vincent Herbert, who is also husband of sister Tamar Braxton, and signed a new management deal with Los Angeles -based entertainment/production company 'The Collective'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thatgrapejuice.net/2011/09/toni-braxton-signs-management/ |title=Toni Braxton Signs New Management Deal &#124; ..::That Grape Juice // ThatGrapeJuice.net::.. &#124;&#124; Thirsty? |publisher=Thatgrapejuice.net |date=September 6, 2011 |accessdate=May 5, 2012}}</ref>

Braxton completed filming of ''[[The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure]]'' alongside [[Jaime Pressly]] and [[Cloris Leachman]] which was released in 2012. Her character&nbsp;<U+2014> Rosalie Rosebud&nbsp;<U+2014> is a singer, whose over-the-top personality was apparently inspired by [[Mariah Carey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/538/ms_impulsive/ |title=Toni Braxton interview by Pete Lewis, 'Blues & Soul' May 2010 |publisher=Bluesandsoul.com |date= |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moss |first=Ricki |url=http://www.bet.com/news/celebrities/2012/08/24/watch-toni-braxton-stars-in-childrens-film.html |title=Watch: Toni Braxton Stars in Children's Film &#124; News |publisher=BET |date= |accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref>

Later that year Braxton confirmed work on her eighth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://welovetoni.com/forum/topics/breaking-news-toni-is-working-with-l-a-reid-on-new-album |title=BREAKING NEWS: Toni is working with L.A. Reid on new album |publisher=www.WeLoveToni.com |date=October 28, 2011 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> Braxton announced at Mercedes-Benz 2012 Fall/Winter Fashion Week in an interview with Rocco Leo Gaglioti as a part of "Fashion News Live", that she would be releasing a new single titled "[[I Heart You]]" in March 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toyazworld.com/2012/02/10/toni-braxton-confirms-new-single-i-heart-you/#more-14993|title=Toni Braxton confirms new single 'I Heart You'...|publisher=ToyazWorld.com}}</ref> Braxton premiered "I Heart You" on March 9, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author=About The Author Pro Motion |url=http://blog.promotion-us.com/exclusive-mp3-toni-braxton-i-heart-you |title=Exclusive: Toni Braxton <U+2018>I Heart You<U+2019> |publisher=Blog.promotion-us.com |date=March 9, 2012 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> The song has peaked at number 1 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Dance/Club play chart.<ref>{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=toni braxton|chart=all}}</ref> The music video for "I Heart You" was directed by [[Bille Woodruff]]. Shortly after the release of [[I Heart You]] rumors began circulating that Braxton would soon retire. These rumors would later be confirmed by Braxton herself On February 7, 2013. Braxton flew to Canada to begin shooting for her lead role in ''Twist of Faith'' later that year. Braxton appeared on Good Morning America to promote her new movie when she also confirmed the rumors of her retirement revealing that she is retiring from music and stated that she would like to focus on acting: "I have to do shows here and there, but I<U+2019>m not gonna do any albums, I<U+2019>m falling out of love with it, it<U+2019>s weird. I don<U+2019>t know what to say when I hear songs. They don<U+2019>t impact me. I<U+2019>ve been trying to listen to songs, record companies have been calling me, so it<U+2019>s a good situation to be in, but I<U+2019>m not really interested at all".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/387118/toni-braxton-retiring-from-music-to-focus-on-film-career |title=Toni Braxton Retiring From Music to Focus on Film Career |publisher=E! Online |date=February 11, 2013 |accessdate=February 17, 2013}}</ref> ''Twist of Faith'' premiered on the [[Lifetime Movie Network]] February 9, 2013.

===2013<U+2013>Present: ''Love, Marriage and Divorce'', Return to Broadway and ''Unbreak My Heart: A Memoir''===
In June 2013, Braxton announced that she was returning to music with a Summer Tour and that she was in the studio working on her eighth studio album. She also stated that the album will not be a traditional album but rather a collaboration album featuring long-time collaborator [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]]. The album will entirely consist of duets between Braxton and Babyface. Babyface said that "The whole perspective is guy and girl, Mars vs. Venus. Even if you're in love, you're in love for different reasons", while Braxton added: <U+201C>I think because Babyface and I have both gone through divorces, we can relate and we can collaborate together on this topic and make it so others who have gone through this situation can relate". The album ''[[Love, Marriage & Divorce]]'' will be released on February 4, 2014, under [[Motown Records]]. The [[2013 Summer Tour]] kicked off in Las Vegas on August 9, 2013 and ended in Atlanta on August 31, 2013. The lead single from ''[[Love, Marriage & Divorce]]'' "Hurt You" premiered on August 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2013/08/17/new-music-toni-braxton-babyface-hurt-you/ |title=New Music: Toni Braxton & Babyface <U+2013> <U+2018>Hurt You<U+2019> |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=2013-08-17 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://singersroom.com/content/2013-06-11/Toni-Braxton-Babyface-Unite-For-Duet-Album-Can-The-Duo-Make-A-Hit-Again/ |title=News &#124; Toni Braxton & Babyface Unite For Duet Album, Can The Duo Make A Hit Again? |publisher=Singersroom |date=June 11, 2013 |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> The song attained success, claiming the No. 1 spot on two charts: the Billboard Adult R&B Songs chart for four weeks, and the Urban Adult Contemporary (Urban AC) for the week ending Dec. 14, 2013. This marked Braxton's first No. 1 hit on the Adult R&B Songs chart since her 2000 release "Just Be a Man About It" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://singersroom.com/content/2013-12-11/Toni-Braxton-and-Babyfaces-Hurt-You-Hits-No1-On-Two-Charts-Fantasia-Soars/|title=Toni Braxton and Babyface<U+2019>s <U+2018>Hurt You<U+2019> Hits No.1 On Two Charts |publisher=Singersroom | date=December 11, 2013}}</ref> The song also hit number 16 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Hot R&B/ Hip Hop Airplay chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/430180/toni-braxton/chart?f=364|title=Toni Braxton : Chart History|publisher=Billboard.com|accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= |title=Toni Braxton - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref> The second single from the album, "Where Did We Go Wrong?" peaked at No. 11 on the Adult R&B Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://singersroom.com/content/2014-01-21/Toni-Braxton-Babyface-and-Ledisi-Soar-With-Thicke-on-Adult-RB-Songs-Charts/|title=Toni Braxton, Babyface and Ledisi Soar with Thicke on Adult R&B Songs Chart |publisher=Singersroom | date=December 11, 2013}}</ref>

In September 2013, it was announced that Braxton would make her return to Broadway alongside collaborator [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] in Broadway's ''After Midnight''.  They are scheduled to perform from March 18<U+2013>31, 2014 at the Brooks Atkinson Theatre.  In succession, they will be third in rotation in the role of "Special Guest Star" following [[Fantasia Barrino]] and [[KD Lang]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/toni-braxton-kenny-babyface-edmonds-636524 |title=Toni Braxton and Kenny 'Babyface' Edmonds Join Broadway's 'After Midnight' Lineup |publisher=The Hollywood Reporter |date=2013-09-25 |accessdate=2014-02-01 |first=David |last=Rooney}}</ref>

On January 20, 2014, Braxton announced that she will be releasing a memoir titled ''Unbreak My Heart: A Memoir'' through [[Harper Collins Publishers]]. Braxton will discuss her career success and struggles and the self healing she took charge of after her diagnosis with the auto-immune disease lupus and her son's diagnosis with autism. ''Unbreak My Heart: A Memoir'' is due to be released May 20, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/music/240653651.html |title=Toni Braxton memoir, 'Unbreak My Heart,' coming in May; to cover her hit songs, lupus |publisher=Star Tribune |date=2014-01-16 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref>

==Artistry==
Braxton has been recognized for her distinctive [[dramatic contralto]] voice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2012-03-24/entertainment/hc-toni-braxtons-concert-at-foxwoods-20120324_1_toni-braxton-angel-break-concert-review|title=Concert Review: Toni Braxton's Sultry Delivery Scores At Foxwoods|last=Kintner|first=Thomas|date=March 24, 2012|publisher=courant.com|accessdate=August 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name="books.google.ca">{{Cite book|title=Rock-N-Roll Gold Rush |last=Dean |first= Maury|authorlink= |year= 2003|publisher= Algora Publishing|location= |isbn= 0-87586-207-1|page= 34|url=http://books.google.com/?id=lJS4EArRBwoC&dq=Rock-N-Roll+Gold+Rush+mariah+carey&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&q=whitney+houston#PPA34,M1}}</ref> Her voice has been called "husky, sultry, elegant and sexy."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myplay.com/artists/toni-braxton|title=My Play: Toni Braxton}}</ref> Due to the huskiness of her voice, Braxton often used male singers such as [[Michael McDonald (singer)|Michael McDonald]], [[Luther Vandross]] and [[Stevie Wonder]] as vocal style models.<ref>{{cite web|last=Huey |first=Steve |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/toni-braxton-mn0000935330 |title=Toni Braxton&nbsp;<U+2014> Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref> [[Chaka Khan]] and [[Anita Baker]] were two of the few female singers that she could stylize. Steve Huey of [[Allmusic]] cites a key to Braxton's success is the versatility of her voice, which he states as being "soulful enough for [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] audiences, but smooth enough for [[adult contemporary]]; sophisticated enough for adults, but sultry enough for younger listeners; strong enough in the face of heartbreak to appeal to women, but ravishing enough to nab the fellas."

Braxton began her career singing traditional R&B and adult contemporary ballads and love songs on her debut and second albums. However, [[hip-hop soul]] and [[dance music]] elements begun to get spun into her sound on ''The Heat'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-heat-mw0000256509|title=The Heat Review}}</ref> ''More Than a Woman'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/more-than-a-woman-mw0000224666|title=More Than A Woman}}</ref> and ''Pulse''. She also showcased her classical training while performing in Broadway plays ''[[Beauty and the Beast]]'' and ''[[Aida]]'' as well as her duet with [[Il Divo]], "The Time of Our Lives".

==Legacy==

Toni Braxton became an immediate R&B superstar after the release of her first album. LA Reid stated during an interview with [[Vh1]]: "We called her the first lady of LaFace. She was our Diva. [[Clive Davis|Clive]] had [[Whitney Houston|Whitney]], [[Tommy Mottola|Tommy]] had [[Mariah Carey|Mariah]] and we had Toni." BBC called the album "spiritedly, mature soul at its best <U+2013> and just urban enough to make it the bedroom album for the hip hop generation." <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/j4fd |title=Music - Review of Toni Braxton - Toni Braxton |publisher=BBC |date=1993-07-13 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref> Braxton had the sound of R&B greats like [[Anita Baker]] and the sex appeal to compete with fellow superstars [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Whitney Houston]]. Over the span of her career Braxton has sold over 66 million records worldwide.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} Braxton's musical catalog contains many classics that have won her many accolades. Her greatest is "[[Un-Break My Heart]]", the [[Diane Warren]]-penned ballad that spent 11-weeks at number 1. Bob McCann, author of ''Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television'' (2010), considered it "simply one of the most haunting R&B records ever made." Reviewer Mark Edward Nero named it one of the best R&B break-up songs and considered it Braxton's "finest moment". He further commented, "damn, this song is so sad it can make people cry for hours at a time." It's Braxton's ability to capture her audience that plays a factor in her continuous success.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} Braxton is a recipient of six [[Grammy Award]]s, seven [[American Music Awards]], and nine [[Billboard Music Awards]].{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

Throughout Braxton's career she made several impacts on fashion mostly for her legendary high splits in her dresses. Her now famous [[Richard Tyler (designer)|Richard Tyler]] white satin gown has gone down in history as one of the most revealing and sexiest dresses. In 2011, Braxton topped the list for the [[Grammy Award]]'s best dressed of the decade.<ref>{{cite news|author=February 10, 2011, 7:54 PM |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/grammy-fashion-the-best-and-worst-of-the-decade/ |title=Grammy Fashion: The Best and Worst of the Decade |publisher=CBS News |date=2011-02-10 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref> "I've always gone a little risque with all my other award show outfits." <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/racy-grammy-dresses-419267#2-toni-braxton |title=Racy Grammy Dresses |publisher=Hollywood Reporter |date=2013-02-08 |accessdate=2014-02-01 |first=Emily |last=Helwig}}</ref> In 2012, Braxton made the list for [[VH1]'s] 50 Greatest Women in Music. Braxton's 2000 performance at [[Super Bowl XXXIV]] is ranked as one of the most memorable Super Bowl performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/02/the-super-bowl-top-5-memorable-halftime-shows/ |title=The Super Bowl: Top 5 Memorable Halftime Shows - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2012-02-03 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref> Braxton cemented her diva status in the music industry in 2006, with her Las Vegas residency ''Toni Braxton: Revealed'', by becoming the first African American performer in Las Vegas to have her act enter the top ten Vegas shows charting.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} Braxton also made headlines for her signature and legendary Giantto Million Dollar Microphone that she performed every show with. Braxton said: "I think it's a great element to the show. You have to have a little sprinkle of [[Liberace]] and this is my little sprinkle of that." Braxton's famous prop was made up of white gold and encrusted with 650 karats of diamonds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/2006/09/01/braxtons-million-dollar-baby/ |title=Braxton's Million Dollar Baby |publisher=TMZ.com |date=2006-01-09 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref> The microphone reportedly cost $1 million.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

Braxton's legacy has inspired countless other artists. For example, R&B artist [[Sevyn Streeter]] cites Braxton as an influence on her career. Streeter posted to her website after meeting Braxton at the [[Soul Train Awards]]: "Ran into this remarkable woman @tonibraxton backstage at the @soultrain awards!!!! yup, I freaked out .....can't tell in this pic but the freak out was real Lol!" R&B singer [[Fantasia Barrino|Fantasia]] confessed her admiration for Braxton in an interview with ''Singer's Room'': "I watched the Braxton show and I was listening to Toni Braxton...she was talking about how she lost the passion and the love for music, and I almost broke down and cried." <ref>{{cite web|url=http://singersroom.com/content/2013-05-15/EXCLUSIVE-Fantasia-Talks-Personal-Album-Almost-Quitting-Toni-Braxton-Not-Doing-Music-More/#jKu4mmstryprt8xj.99 |title=Videos &#124; EXCLUSIVE: Fantasia Talks Personal Album, Almost Quitting, Toni Braxton Not Doing Music, More |publisher=Singersroom |date=2013-05-15 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref> Braxton has also been referenced by many of today's Hip-Hop/R&B artist such as [[Ludacris]] in the song "[[Wet the Bed]]", from [[Chris Brown]]'s album ''[[F.A.M.E. (album)|F.A.M.E.]]'' (2009).{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

==Personal life==

Braxton met musician [[Keri Lewis]] when his group, [[Mint Condition]], opened for her on tour; they married on April 21, 2001. On December 2, 2001, she gave birth to their first child, a son named Denim Cole Braxton-Lewis. In 2002, while gearing up for the release of her fourth studio album, Braxton discovered she was pregnant with her second child; the complicated pregnancy confined her to [[bed rest]]. The couple's second son, Diezel Ky Braxton-Lewis, was born on March 31, 2003. As Diezel has been diagnosed with [[autism]], Braxton has become very involved with [[Autism Speaks]], serving as their International Spokesperson. In November 2009, through her attorney [[Antavius Weems]], Braxton announced that she and her husband had separated. On July 24, 2013, their divorce was finalized after four years of separation.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

Braxton's godsister is Toi Garcia, a former [[Auburn University]] gymnast.<ref>http://www.auburntigers.com/sports/w-gym/mtt/garcia_toi00.html</ref>

===Health problems===
{{BLP unsourced section|date=May 2014}} 
As of August 2007, rumors surfaced that she has been diagnosed with breast cancer. Braxton stated to ''[[Access Hollywood]]'', that the breast cancer rumors were false and that her health is in great condition. However, in 2008, she had a [[Benign tumor|benign]] lump removed from her breast.

On April 8, 2008, near the end of her two-year run at the [[Flamingo Hotel]], Braxton was briefly hospitalized and the remaining dates on the show, which was scheduled to end on August 23, 2008, were canceled. Later, while appearing on Season 7 of ''Dancing with the Stars'', she stated, that she has been diagnosed with [[Microangiopathy|microvascular angina]] (small vessel disease).

On November 18, 2010, Braxton admitted to [[CBS News]] that she had been diagnosed with [[systemic lupus erythematosus]] (SLE), a potentially life-threatening autoimmune disease. Braxton's brother is also a carrier of the disease, and her uncle died of complications from lupus. While taping her reality series ''[[Braxton Family Values]]'', she went in for surgery. Braxton was hospitalized in [[Los Angeles]] in December 2012 because of "minor health issues" related to [[lupus]].

